  "prompt": "Will there ever be an Asian president?",
  "response": "It's certainly possible for the United States to have a president of Asian descent in the future. The eligibility criteria for becoming U.S. president include being a natural-born U.S. citizen, at least 35 years old, and a resident of the U.S. for at least 14 years. Race or ethnicity is not a factor. \n\nAs the demographics of the U.S. continue to evolve and the Asian American and Pacific Islander (AAPI) community grows in both numbers and political influence, the likelihood increases. There's already a rising number of AAPI individuals holding political office at various levels, which helps to lay the groundwork for future presidential candidates. The eventual election of a president of Asian descent will depend on a wide range of factors, including the political climate, the candidates' platforms, and voter preferences at the time.",
